<subSubSection id="A909BB37E2EF76C75EF4C82CCE1A0FED" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="description">
<paragraph id="08D8B0EC5E08C59C2F11F38322CBF52B" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3CC0328BDA4DAD77DF1E13CFBE3ADCC7" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
Thalli lanceolate when young, becoming somewhat ovate (rarely obovate) when mature; base cuneate, becoming umbilicate; 50-115 mm thick; males to at least 5.5 cm wide and more than 31 cm long; females to 12 cm wide and more than 28 cm long, but thalli mostly narrower; color uniform throughout the thallus except for reproductive areas, olive-green when fresh, drying to grayish or brownish purple. Thalli dioecious. Spermatangia in packets of 2-4 
<normalizedToken id="10E535EA5C320BD391602BB39F3090CD" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-4 
<normalizedToken id="51274F0D1221F8015B004E3639341AF3" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
8. Mature zygotosporangia in packets of 2-4 
<normalizedToken id="F2B138143E2639D896187A67A980EC85" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-4 
<normalizedToken id="D0799688A0069FF415695FFBB51DABAD" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-4. Habitat: mid to high intertidal rock, usually associated with sand. Phenology: winter to early spring (a few thalli may persist as late as mid summer). Distinguished from other species of 
<taxonomicName id="DBBA5EE9C378AD0E5E75993235138973" authorityName="J.Agardh" authorityYear="1899" class="Bangiophyceae" family="Bangiaceae" genus="Pyropia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pyropia" order="Bangiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Rhodophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="D8498DE33405A00CE5A50522F9E49C37" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Pyropia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by unique 
<emphasis id="5154A52B957790FCE4FEDC6E5FB99557" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">rbc</emphasis>
L and 18S rRNA gene sequences.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F50E687493C6FA8BF668418AD8402521" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="holotype">
<paragraph id="740FEE6AAF49E9EC31795FABC9298317" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Holotype.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C87C1B1F6A10D5D3046C5ACF076C495A" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
Saxicolous in the upper mid intertidal on rocks partially buried in sand at the south end of West Beach, Calvert Island, British Columbia, Canada (
<geoCoordinate id="3A5FAF939764BD402A553284710F30C5" degrees="51" direction="north" minutes="39.14" orientation="latitude" precision="9" value="51.652332">51°39.14'N</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate id="42451C0FA8082685D0A0231EA6220504" degrees="128" direction="west" minutes="08.42" orientation="longitude" precision="9" value="-128.14034">128°08.42'W</geoCoordinate>
), 
<emphasis id="D7C20F76C626B6B64A9A57FABB209CAB" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">S.C. Lindstrom 15596</emphasis>
, 18 Feb 2014, 
<emphasis id="BD56DAE93BE31B48F38000F13540364C" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">UBC A90636</emphasis>
. GenBank sequences KP903995, KP903996 (
<emphasis id="479BCE859ABADBA8B7F9401302B01646" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">rbc</emphasis>
L), KP903910 (SSU).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2F48272A6D36D6F9497033412E7E4EF3" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="isotypes">
<paragraph id="5764319AC74AAA8D9316FC9E317DD858" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Isotypes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="142B1B7FCAFAAFECEE3379DD379FD34C" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
SCL 15594 (
<emphasis id="FF029C61D2E2B641E6B6355844304DBB" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">UC 2050591</emphasis>
), SCL 15599 (
<emphasis id="BFF05B0D8D5397D9CDAAF41E29FAD832" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">UBC A90637</emphasis>
), SCL 15600 &amp; 15601 (
<emphasis id="11503B392910857FB744BF5646554A33" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">UBC A90638</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="66B0AE7812F582D8AAB6EAABF0918810" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="0C08BAB7A9EE1818BA0B64A8995FFA40" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="46BFA7E0BD29AEA370A7912AA81CAB64" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
This species is named for the biogeographic region in which it is found, using the terminology of 
<bibRefCitation id="FE362D609E58677D872E09603E0CAF89" author="Valentine, JW" journalOrPublisher="Limnology and Oceanography" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="198 - 211" publicationUrl="10.4319/lo.1966.11.2.0198" refId="B35" refString="Valentine, JW, 1966. Numerical analysis of marine molluscan ranges on the extratropical northeastern Pacific shelf. Limnology and Oceanography 11: 198 - 211, DOI: 10.4319/lo.1966.11.2.0198" title="Numerical analysis of marine molluscan ranges on the extratropical northeastern Pacific shelf." url="10.4319/lo.1966.11.2.0198" volume="11" year="1966">Valentine (1966)</bibRefCitation>
, but with a modification of the boundaries to extend from Cape Mendocino, California, to the central coast of British Columbia. It also commemorates the centenary of the University of British Columbia herbarium, which was established in early 1916.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B5BD879A10707BA413FEDFEA2A0A8C49" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="2E30149D61435F9E7F69731D812CD6D7" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D9ACF6958ACFF4E85B6D6A8283562225" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Calvert Island, British Columbia, Canada, to Cape Mendocino, California, USA.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="680AC1D64F3B0D1ADE9237FFACD0A4A5" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName id="1D9984CDCD03FDCCB3DF9A119EDD4540" authorityName="S. C. Lindstrom &amp; J. R. Hughey" authorityYear="2015" class="Bangiophyceae" family="Bangiaceae" genus="Pyropia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pyropia montereyensis" order="Bangiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Rhodophyta" rank="species" species="montereyensis">
<emphasis id="17106B75E0BF63D32A1D58601848B25C" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Pyropia montereyensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="02701D2BC5D631C440A99D4045F6E92C" authorityName="S. C. Lindstrom" authorityYear="2015" class="Bangiophyceae" family="Bangiaceae" genus="Pyropia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pyropia columbiensis" order="Bangiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Rhodophyta" rank="species" species="columbiensis">
<emphasis id="B88337A6056F712FC69907F61375FD58" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Pyropia columbiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are essentially morphologically identical and represent the southern and northern species of a vicariant pair, respectively.
</paragraph>
